#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""scry-eval — does fusion actually beat the best single model?

Anecdotes ("the fused answer looked better") are not evidence. This measures it.

Two regimes:
  OBJECTIVE   items have a verifiable answer. We score every solo proposer AND the
              fused answer against ground truth with code — no LLM judge, so no
              circularity. The question: is `scry` at least as accurate as the best
              single model, and does it stay correct when a weak member is wrong?
  SUBJECTIVE  open-ended items. A BLIND, order-randomized, FAMILY-NEUTRAL judge
              compares the fused answer against each solo answer. "Family-neutral"
              = for a fused-vs-X matchup we only let a judge whose model family is
              neither the synthesizer's (Claude) nor X's vote, which removes the
              obvious self-enhancement bias. Each pair is judged in BOTH orderings
              to cancel position bias. We report fused's win-rate vs the field and
              vs its single toughest competitor.

  DRACO       Perplexity's deep-research benchmark — the one OpenRouter Fusion
              headlines. Each task ships a weighted rubric (~39 criteria); we grade
              the fused answer (and optionally each solo) against it with the
              OFFICIAL per-criterion MET/UNMET method + normalization from the MIT
              `rubric` scorer, driven by a subscription-CLI grader. Measures OUR
              scry on DRACO's 0–100 scale — NOT a reproduction of OpenRouter's
              headline (their model builds / Exa retrieval / judge differ).

The system under test is the REAL `./scry --json` (we evaluate the shipped CLI,
end-to-end). Judging reuses scry's own provider plumbing (so it speaks to the same
subscription CLIs, including agy's prompt-as-arg path). Pilot-scale by design:
N is tiny, so this VALIDATES THE METHOD and shows direction — it is not a powered
statistical result. Scale up the dataset for that.

Usage:
  ./scry-eval                       # objective + subjective dataset
  ./scry-eval --only objective      # one regime
  ./scry-eval --limit 1             # first N items of each regime (smoke test)
  ./scry-eval --draco --draco-tasks 1                    # DRACO, 1 task (smoke)
  ./scry-eval --draco --draco-stratified --grade-solos   # DRACO, 1 task/domain, fused vs solos
Stdlib only; Python 3.9+.
"""
